defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default What do you think is behind that?
defaultPaul defaultSmeedefault: First of all, I think the lenders’ attitude has contributed. There is a very careful management process, which the industry has signed up to, to manage people who are in arrears. There is much more sophisticated approach to identifying people with problems at an early stage. Second and overwhelmingly, we have had a very long period of flat interest rates, which clearly assists in helping people avoid getting into trouble.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ309 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default Forbearance, the first part of your answer. Is this healthy forbearance or do you think there is a problem brewing in the background? Let us not beat about the bush. These are the lowest interest rates we have seen in 300 years.
defaultPaul defaultSmeedefault: Indeed.
defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default If you are a lender, it is quite an attractive proposition to finance a zombie household or a troubled household, let us say, at 50 basis points rather than lock in what could potentially be quite an unpleasant loss. It is interesting because in your answer you did talk about early identification of troubled households, which is obviously also important. Nonetheless, do you think we have too much forbearance in the system? A lot of people are talking about this. Do you think we might have too much forbearance in the system, which means that when interest rates start rising
default,
default it is going to start revealing quite a lot of holes in households?
defaultPaul defaultSmeedefault: First of all, the most recent study of how many loans were subject to forbearance suggested that there were between 5% and 8% of mortgages. That was done by the regulator.
defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default By value?
defaultPaul defaultSmeedefault: I think that was by number.
defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default Okay. The number that I have been using is 8% by value on £1.2 billion worth of mortgages. There was about £100 billion worth of—that was a Bank of England number, I think.
defaultPaul defaultSmeedefault: The estimate, which was again done by the regulator, was that about 5% of those households would have been in arrears for more than six months had they not been in forbearance. There are two thoughts on this. First, just because you go into forbearance does not mean you stick in forbearance and I think this has been a system by which people have been helped over a difficult point rather than a state of life into which they have existed. 
defaultThe second question that you raised concerned indebtedness and what happens when interest rates rise and clearly this is something we are planning around and thinking through. The evidence that we took when we did a major research study a couple of years ago was that most people had strategies available to them for coping with small, phased step-ups in the interest rate, up to about four increases over a period of time. They had ways in which they would adjust their lifestyle so they continued to meet their mortgage obligations. We will be updating that research in some way over the coming months.
defaultOne comment I would make is that if these people had been regularly paying their mortgages on a repayment basis, as a lot of have, during the course of the years of low interest rates they will have been paying down their debt. So they will be in a better position when the interest rates do start picking up.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ310 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default It is quite a dynamic picture this. You are absolutely right, there are a lot of people who have been paying this down. There are different ways you can skin this particular cat. The Bank of England also comes up with numbers that say if you see a two percentage point increase in the base rate we are going to see up to 28%, I think it is, of households having to make some significant changes to their standard of living in order to accommodate that. There is another set of numbers that say 42% of households currently cannot afford an unexpected £300 bill, which is also quite alarming. 
defaultThe problem is there is a Venn diagram and, at the end of the day, what you are ultimately trying to find is where those households are getting hit by the most of them and what the value of the outstanding debt is. So what are the implications on the banking market but also what are the social implications? As legislators, what we have to look at most carefully is, by looking at this Venn diagram, how many households we think are going to be in serious trouble when the interest rates inevitably go up and when the tide comes in we see which households are h
defaultoled
default below the waterline. Does anybody have any idea?
defaultPaul defaultSmeedefault: I will pause for a second and say if you are talking about a 2% increase
default,
default you will probably then be in an economic situation where people’s incomes are increasing and so their ability to cope will also be increasing. We do not have—
defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default Assuming that distribution is even.
defaultPaul defaultSmeedefault: Indeed, I accept that. I would have thought by the time you had a 2% increase
default,
default you would believe that that was fairly wide based.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ311 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default The only reason I am very cautious about this—I am sorry to keep interrupting you—is that we talk about a 2% increase in interest rates as something pretty heinous and major. Actually it is not. It is just going back to a normal low level of interest rate. It is just going back to something vaguely normal. We have a super-loose monetary policy. We are just going back to a very loose monetary policy with a 2% increase in interest rates. The problem is, when you are right down at this level, a 2% increase in interest rates is a fivefold increase in funding costs. This is quite important when you are looking at the cost of forbearance for banks and then the knock-on effect on to households.
defaultChair:default It is particular relevant with high loan-to-value ratios, which we are encouraging at the moment.
defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default Yes, and an over-inflated value of property.
defaultChair:default We will allow you to say something now.
defaultPaul defaultSmeedefault: I am not sure whether I should just say, “Well, I agree”. You make very valid points. The issue for us is the way in which we, first of all, identify and, second, help manage those who are liable to get into this sort of difficulty. Since the last time there was a high level of arrears, I believe the sophistication and consideration with which lenders handle those in difficult situations has improved significantly, which I think is positive.
defaultQ312 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default You do not think that that is as a result of the fact that they can be more generous because the funding costs are so low?
defaultPaul defaultSmeedefault: I think there are other inhibitions from external authorities on them as well, but I think it is also a cultural change that has gone on within the lending community.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ313 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default Just one last point on the mortgage rescue scheme, which is something that was to help people out. That is now due to end in March 2014. When that goes
default,
default what do you think the effect on that is going to be? There are a lot of things happening at the same time and this is disappearing. My twofold question is, do you think we are going to see an increase in defaults and the second point is do you think that might see a change in culture back to being a bit more hard-nosed on the part of the mortgage lenders?
defaultPaul defaultSmeedefault: Relatively few people have accessed the mortgage rescue scheme, which is one of the reasons why it has been removed. I think it was a very useful catalyst for driving a change in culture, but I think the change in approach is now so embedded that I would not regard the removal of the scheme as indicative that the culture would necessarily change.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ314 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default A final question with probably a yes or no answer. Do you think that when interest rates start going up we will see an increase in the number of defaults?
defaultPaul defaultSmeedefault: Yes, 
defaultmathematically 
defaultthat is probably the case. I do not over-exaggerate the rate at which the increase will happen or the speed with which it will happen either. There may be an uptick from the very low levels. As you say, we are at very low levels now. There may be an uptick, but do not think in terms of tens of thousands back to the 1990s.
defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default You do not give me any sense that you are particularly worried about a floodgate of defaults coming through.
defaultPaul defaultSmeedefault: I do not believe there is a floodgate that will open. I believe that it is better managed than that.
defaultMark defaultGarnierdefault:default It could pick up but it will still be quite low?
defaultPaul defaultSmeedefault: It may pick up, but it will still be relatively low because of the changes that have happened in the intervening years.
